    {
        "content": "<p>Linear transformations are central to my engineering work in medical imaging research, as many imaging schemes can be modeled as linear transformations from imaging targets to observations. To understand linear transformations (and imaging systems) better - and in particular how they can be stuck together - I want to learn more about what kind of constructions on linear transformations are induced by common categorical constructions.</p>\n<p>To do this, I would like to learn more about the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{LinTran}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">i</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">T</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">r</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">n</span></span></span></span></span> (is there a standard name?) where the objects are linear transformations between finite dimensional vector spaces, the morphisms are commutative squares from one linear transformation to another, and composition is done component-wise. In particular, I would like to figure out what limits and colimits exist, and what linear transformations (and matrices) they correspond to. To begin with, it might make sense to think about initial or terminal objects, but I'm especially interested in limits over diagrams of shape <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⋅</mo><mo>→</mo><mo>⋅</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\cdot \\to \\cdot</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.44445em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⋅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.44445em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⋅</span></span></span></span>, as this corresponds to two interlinked linear transformations, and so to two interlinked imaging systems. (Interlinked imaging systems are relevant to thinking about imaging schemes involving multiple related observers / observations).</p>\n<p>I don't yet know a good way to begin learning about a new (to me!) category of interest, being new to category theory. I suspect this category is well-studied, but am not sure what it might be called.</p>\n<p>Any hints (general or specific) are appreciated!</p>",
        "id": 193270920,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1586314076
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It looks to me like this category lacks something about linear transformations : there is no operation of composition of the linear transformations! I mean you could try to add a monoidal product (ie a way to combine objects together), but it is not defined for all pairs of objects. That is not to say that there is nothing interesting about the category you are considering : you might be able to see many cool things with it, but keep in mind that's not the whole picture. </p>\n<p>I believe, what you want to define here is rather a \"double category\" : that's like a category, but with vertical morphisms and horizontal morphisms, plus 2-cells (ie morphisms between morphisms), that have shape of a square. Here the objects would be vector spaces, the horizontal and vertical morphsism would be the linear transformations, and the 2-cells, the commutative squares. This kind of objects might be scary if you are new to category, so probably best not to go too deep into this too quickly, but I think it's good to keep this in mind as well</p>",
        "id": 193287671,
        "sender_full_name": "Thibaut Benjamin",
        "timestamp": 1586334069
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's a standard construction called an arrow category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo>→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal C^\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6198089999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> that you can make from any category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span>, where objects of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo>→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal C^\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6198089999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> are morphisms in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span> and morphisms in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo>→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal C^\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6198089999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> are commutative squares in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span>. It sounds like you're talking about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{FVect}^\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.695819em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01597em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">t</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.695819em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1390100000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 193293288,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1586337582
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and good news: the questions you are asking probably have well-established answers if this is what you have in mind :-)</p>",
        "id": 193330046,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1586357076
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>for example, if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span></span> is complete or cocomplete, then so is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo>→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}^\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6198089999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 193330209,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1586357156
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>or more generally, if it has limits or colimits of a given shape, then so does <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo>→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}^\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6198089999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 193330307,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1586357192
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(this follows from the fact that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi><mo>→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}^\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6198089999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is equivalently the category of functors from the \"single-nontrivial-arrow category\" <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>→</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">0 \\to 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{C}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05834em;\">C</span></span></span></span></span>, and the fact that if a category has all limits or colimits of a given shape, then so does the category of functors from a given domain into that codomain)<br>\n(also, in such a scenario, the limits/colimits are computed pointwise)</p>",
        "id": 193330536,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1586357300
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By the way, algebraists call the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}^{\\to}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7041489999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7041489999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> \"the category of representations of the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A_2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> quiver\", and they know shitloads about that.  </p>\n<p>A <strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quiver_(mathematics)\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quiver_(mathematics)\">quiver</a></strong> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">Q</span></span></span></span> is a graph, and we can freely turn any quiver into a category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>Q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F(Q)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">Q</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, and then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>Q</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}^{F(Q)}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.97234em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.97234em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.14734em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">Q</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is called the <strong>category of representations</strong> of the quiver <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">Q</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>They call the graph with <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">n</span></span></span></span> objects and a chain of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n-1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> composable arrows <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 193339093,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1586360801
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A quiver has <strong>finite type</strong> if it has finitely many isomorphism classes of <strong>indecomposable</strong> representations: ones that aren't direct sums (=coproducts) of others in a nontrivial way.   <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabriel%27s_theorem\" title=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gabriel%27s_theorem\">Gabriel's theorem</a> classifies the quivers of finite type, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> has finite type.</p>",
        "id": 193339559,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1586361006
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is an amazing theorem, because it sets up connections between quivers and other nice things.</p>",
        "id": 193339651,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1586361050
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyway, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}^{\\to}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7041489999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7041489999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> has 3 indecomposable objects.  If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span> is our field these are:</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo><mover><mo><mo>⟶</mo></mo><mn>1</mn></mover></mo><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> k \\stackrel{1}{\\longrightarrow} k </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.273108em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mop op-limits\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.262108em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span><span class=\"mop\">⟶</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.7110000000000003em;margin-left:0em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span><br>\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo><mover><mo><mo>⟶</mo></mo><mn>0</mn></mover></mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> k \\stackrel{0}{\\longrightarrow} 0 </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.273108em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mop op-limits\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.262108em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span><span class=\"mop\">⟶</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.7110000000000003em;margin-left:0em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span><br>\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo><mover><mo><mo>⟶</mo></mo><mn>0</mn></mover></mo><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> 0 \\stackrel{0}{\\longrightarrow} k </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.273108em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mop op-limits\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.262108em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span><span class=\"mop\">⟶</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.7110000000000003em;margin-left:0em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>Every object of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">V</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">→</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Vect}^{\\to}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7041489999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">V</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">c</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7041489999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">→</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is isomorphic to a direct sum of copies of these.</p>",
        "id": 193340967,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1586361608
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>o:</p>",
        "id": 193348122,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1586364817
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what about the function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span></span> given by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>↦</mo><mn>1.5</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x \\mapsto 1.5x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.522em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span><span class=\"mord\">5</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">x</span></span></span></span>?</p>",
        "id": 193348160,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1586364831
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's an isomorphism, so in particular isomorphic to the identity on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span></span> <span aria-label=\"tada\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f389\" role=\"img\" title=\"tada\">:tada:</span></p>",
        "id": 193348828,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1586365134
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, everyone. This gives me some good direction to do some reading.</p>",
        "id": 193351102,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1586366187
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>hmm, hold on...</p>",
        "id": 193371789,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1586376277
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oooh, i was glossing \"object of Vect^→ [...] isomorphic to\" in my head as \"morphism of Vect [...] is\" in my head w/o thinking about it</p>",
        "id": 193371985,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1586376388
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but i suppose \"is\" for morphisms of Vect is equality, whereas \"isomorphism\" for objects of Vect^→ is considerably weaker</p>",
        "id": 193372010,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1586376408
    },
    {
